      <div class="projectDetail">
        <p>In early 2005, about 6 months prior to the opening of the Cross-City Tunnel, VLC was engaged by the Australian Outdoor Media Association to estimate traffic demand for the tunnel in the year after its opening.&#160; The Association was concerned that the project's extremely high traffic forecasts of more than 90,000 vehicles per weekday (vpwd) as documented in the project's Environmental Impact Statement &#160;would severely impact on the number of vehicles passing outdoor advertising signs in inner Sydney. They were especially concerned about those billboards located on William Street, which parallels the tunnel.&#160; If the forecasts in the EIS proved to be correct, then the revenue derived from numerous billboards would be compromised.</p>
        <p>VLC's Zenith model forecast that the tunnel would only carry about 30,000 vpwd in its first year of operation, so our advice to the Association was "do not panic - let's see what happens".&#160; VLC's forecasts proved to be very close to the mark.</p>
        <p>In 2010, the new owners of the failed toll tunnel (Cross City Motorways Ltd) engaged VLC to assess the impact on tunnel traffic and toll revenue resulting from the removal of road closures and the narrowing of William Street (road capacity restraint measures that had been agreed with the Government).</p>
        <p>VLC's assessment of toll revenue loss to the company was submitted to the RTA for their consideration.&#160; Negotiations continue between the RTA and Cross City Motorways.</p>
      </div>

