      <div class="projectDetail">
        <p>In 2005, VLC was commissioned to perform an audit role for one of the bidders for the Lane Cove Tunnel project.</p>
        <p>Traffic forecasts for the project, as published in the EIS were in excess of 100,000 vehicles per day for 2008. The lead consultants for at least two of the bidders came up with even higher forecasts. One consultant, for example, predicted that 180,000 vehicles would use the tunnel per day by 2021, a physical impossibility.</p>
        <p>VLC, in reporting to a committee comprising of four banks considering taking equity in the project, could not entertain traffic forecasts of this scale. It was VLC's view that even the traffic numbers reported in the EIS were grossly optimistic as Epping Road, the road immediately above the tunnel, was only carrying 65,000 vehicles per day. VLC's advice, which did not require the assistance of modelling, was that the project could only be expected to carry about 60,000 vehicles per day in its early years.</p>
        <p>On opening, the tunnel carried approximately 55,000 vehicles per day. It now carries approximately 65,000 vehicles per day.</p>
        <p>Subsequent to the project experiencing financial difficulties because of low traffic usage, VLC was engaged to produce investment grade forecasts for ABN Amro, enabling them to sell their equity and minimise their losses.</p>
